observations.recommendation:
a. Provide the Municipal Assessor’s Office with adequate manpower complement and facilities. If necessary, capacitate the personnel and require to attend in formal training on the proper assessment procedures;

b. Direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to conduct tax mapping and comply with their duties and functions as stipulated in Section 472 (b) of Article III of RA No. 7160 and Section I.C.1 (a) to (d) of Chapter I under Local Government Assessment Organization of the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations; and

c. Direct the OIC-Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer to closely coordinate and ensure that the assessment data/information in their respective records are duly reconciled and updated;

a. Direct the OIC - Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer to examine and reconcile their respective assessment data to generate a reliable and accurate assessment record/report; 
b. After reconciliation, direct the Municipal Treasurer to furnish the Municipal Accountant the RPTAR/Taxpayer’s Index or Taxpayer’s index card showing the name of tax payers and the amount due; 
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant to establish record RPT and SET Receivables, at the beginning of the year, based on the RPTAR/Taxpayer’s Index for the current year provided by the Municipal Treasurer. Draw appropriated adjusting entries, if necessary; 
d. Direct the Municipal Treasurer to strengthen/intensify tax campaign and collection efforts to increase efficiency especially in collecting tax delinquencies. Impose penalties and enforce legal means in its collection efforts. Regularly monitor and assess collection performance not only on the target parameters provided by oversight agencies but also on the actual due and collectible RPT/SET for the current year.

a. Provide the Municipal Assessor’s Office with adequate manpower complement and facilities. If necessary, capacitate the personnel and require to attend in formal training on the proper assessment procedures; 
b. Direct the Municipal Assessor’s Office to conduct tax mapping and comply with their duties and functions as stipulated in Section 472 (b) of Article III of RA No. 7160 and Section I.C.1 (a) to (d) of Chapter I under Local Government Assessment Organization of the Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations; 
c. Direct the OIC- Municipal Assessor and the Municipal Treasurer to closely coordinate and ensure that the assessment data/information in their respective records are duly reconciled and updated; and 
d. Ascertain at all times, that real property assessments are accurate and reliable as basis of collection by the Treasurer’s Office.

a. Direct the Municipal Accountant to institute sound Perpetual Inventory system pursuant to the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) for Local Government Units (LGUs) to account for the recording of receipt and issuance of inventories; 
b. Require the Municipal Accountant to record inventories upon receipt of procured/donated Drugs and Medicines, and Medical, Dental, and Laboratory Supplies, recognize the corresponding expenses only upon consumption or distribution, maintain subsidiary ledger cards and properly classify the income and expense accounts; 
c. Direct the GSO to require the RHU, DRRMO, and other offices in custody of and in-charge to distribute the procured/donated drugs and medicines, and Medical, Dental, and Laboratory Supplies to submit monthly RIS as basis on the preparation of RSMI/SSMI to account for the issued/consumed inventories. The RSMI/SSMI together with the RIS shall be submitted to the Municipal Accountant. Based on the RSMI/SSMI, the Municipal Accountant shall draw a JEV to record the expenditures using appropriate expenditure accounts; and 
d. Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical inventory of drugs and medicines and medical, dental and laboratory supplies quarterly and reconcile its records periodically with the accounting record.

We recommended and Management agreed to the following:
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to analyze and reconcile the discrepancy between the balances in the books and per physical count of the PPE accounts;
Direct the GSO to initiate the process of disposing the unserviceable properties as listed in the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP).
Direct the Municipal Accountant, after receiving necessary documents, to record the dropping off of the unserviceable properties from the books of accounts
Direct the Municipal Accountant to make necessary adjustments to book up the donated properties at fair value.;
Require the Municipal Accountant and the GSO to maintain complete property and ledger cards as required in Sections 114 and 120, Volume 1 of the NGAS for LGUs;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct regularly a year-end physical inventory on Property, Plant and Equipment and submit it to the Accounting Unit for reconciliation of balances to ensure correctness and reliability of the PPE account balances;
Require the GSO to annually provide a copy of the reconciled RCPPE to the COA, not later than January 31st of the ensuing year, showing therein the proper classification of PPE; and
If possible, provide additional manpower to assist the GSO in performing the rigorous task required of their office.

Require the Municipal Assessor to comply with his duties and functions as stipulated in Section 472 of the Local Government Code and Manual on Real Property Appraisal and Assessment Operations;

Provide the Municipal Assessor’s Office with a qualified and able tax mapper as well as the adequate manpower to do the tax mapping activity, ocular inspection and other relevant functions of the said office;

Submit updated Report on Assessment to the Provincial Assessor’s Office to provide them an accurate information relevant to their plan for a possible general revision; and

Furnish the Municipal Treasurer’s Office with the updated and accurate data on RPT Assessment which serves as basis for RPT target and collection every year.

Establish a Municipal Council for the Protection of Children;

Allocate at least 1% of their IRA for Programs, Projects and Activities for children’s welfare; and 

Strictly comply with the rules and regulations about the formulation and utilization of the 1% LCPC fund.

Require the Municipal Assessor to register all real estate owned by municipality under the Torrens Title System pursuant to COA Circular No. 92-386;

Cause the cancellation of the three (3) Tax Declaration still in the name of the former owners and its transfer in the name of the LGU;

Require the Sangguniang Bayan to appropriate funds needed to secure Torrens Title for the LGU’s real estate;  and

Upon the completion of the Torrens Title, the Municipal Accountant should prepare the necessary entries to book-up the fair/market value in the books of the municipality in order to fairly present the Property, Plant and Equipment (PPE) - Land and Government Equity accounts in the financial statements.

Direct the General Services Office (GSO) and Accounting Department to coordinate and conduct a thorough analysis to identify and reconcile the discrepancies in their respective records of PPE;

Require the GSO to regularly update the property cards and for the Accounting Department to regularly update the PPE Ledger Cards in order to facilitate inventory taking, check and balance, and timely adjustments in the PPE accounts, whenever required;

Perform periodic reconciliation of property records to ensure that all discrepancies are   immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts;

Effect the proper classification of PPE accounts in the RPCPPE. Accounts used by the GSO and the Accounting Department should be consistent and in accordance with the applicable accounting standards;

Require the GSO to record the actual carrying cost or value of the property which has no corresponding cost in the RPCPPE. In case of donated property, the amount reflected in the delivery documents shall be the carrying cost of the property. In the absence of such documents, an Appraisal Committee shall be created to obtain an accurate valuation of carrying cost or value of all the donated property and all other property that has no assigned value. After which, the Appraisal Committee shall render a report or narrative report related thereto, and the same shall be furnished to the Accountant to effect proper adjustments; and

Submit the corrected RPCPPE duly reconciled with the accounting records.

Present the details of specific projects and activities to be undertaken in the Annual Budget; 

Explore and implement other viable initiatives to increase collection from SWM services to generate sufficient amount needed for SWM programs; and 

Procure and utilize the fund allocated for SWM in accordance with Section 6 of Rule XV, Part IV and Section 3.3 of DILG-DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017.

